explanation:
OS_CHECK_POINTER - This macro is used directly in the target function. Its expansion may contain if-statements or do-while(0) constructs that introduce controlling expressions inside the target function; those expanded controlling expressions determine whether the MISRA rule on invariant controlling expressions is violated (for example a while(0) is an invariant but permitted under the documented exception). You must inspect the macro body to decide compliance.

OS_printf - Often used inside OS_CHECK_POINTER expansions for diagnostic logging. If OS_CHECK_POINTER uses conditional logging (e.g. if/else around OS_printf) the controlling expressions in those constructs must be checked. Including OS_printf lets the analyzer follow any control flow inside the macro expansion that references it.

UtAssert_Abort - The unit-test/assert helper appears in the static graph and may be used by OS_CHECK_POINTER in test builds (e.g. assertions that abort on NULL). If the macro calls assertion helpers, those calls or the surrounding conditional/loop expressions must be examined for invariant controlling expressions.

OS_ObjectIdFindByName - Although this is only called (not expanded) in the target function, include its symbol to confirm it is an actual function call (no macro expansion in-place) and therefore does not introduce additional controlling expressions inside the target function body. This helps separate violations that are inside the target function (or its macros) from those inside called functions.

OS_INVALID_POINTER - The error-return constant(s) used by OS_CHECK_POINTER (named here as OS_INVALID_POINTER as an example) are needed to understand how the macro alters control flow (e.g. immediate return vs. set-and-continue). Knowing the exact return/error symbol(s) used by the macro is necessary to conclude whether the macro uses an invariant controlling expression that affects the target function.

Note: The primary required symbol to decide MISRA compliance for this function is the definition of OS_CHECK_POINTER and any symbols/macros it expands to. The other symbols listed are those commonly referenced by that macro (from the static call graph) and are included so the analyzer can fully inspect any control constructs introduced by macro expansion or test-build variants.
